  "transcript": [
    {
      "turn": 1,
      "role": "maya",
      "content": "Hi Aarti, I hope you're having a calm morning. I noticed your study ritual with classical music — does it still help you focus on tricky English terms?"
    },
    {
      "turn": 2,
      "role": "user",
      "content": "Yeah, it does... sometimes. Today, my head feels heavy, like \"dhokla\" after a big meal. The music helps, but I’m just so tired. My revision is lagging. Ugh."
    },
    {
      "turn": 2,
      "role": "maya",
      "content": "Hi Aarti, I get that heavy feeling — like after too much spicy biryani! Take it slow. What part of pharmacology is giving you trouble today?"
    },
    {
      "turn": 3,
      "role": "user",
      "content": "Oh, you got the \"heavy head\" part right! It’s not pharmacology exactly… it’s the English terms in the PG notes. Words like “idiosyncratic” or “pharmacokinetics” — they look like puzzles. I mix up the prefixes. Maybe we can do a quick vocab drill? Or should I just rest?"
    },
    {
      "turn": 3,
      "role": "maya",
      "content": "Hi Aarti, you used \"idiosyncratic\" perfectly! Tiny tweak: we often say \"pharmacokinetics\" as one word, but your meaning was clear. You decide — want to practice a few terms, or take a short break?"
    },
    {
      "turn": 4,
      "role": "user",
      "content": "Let’s try a quick drill… but just 5 minutes, okay? My eyes are half-closed already."
    },
    {
      "turn": 4,
      "role": "maya",
      "content": "Hi Aarti, ready when you are! Let’s start with “idiosyncratic.” Imagine it as \"idiots have their own quirks!\" What’s next? “Pharmacokinetics” — think \"pharma\" (drugs) + \"kinetics\" (movement). Any other term on your mind?"
    },
    {
      "turn": 5,
      "role": "user",
      "content": "Teratogenic\" — I always mix it with \"tachycardic.\" Help? 😅"
    },
    {
      "turn": 5,
      "role": "maya",
      "content": "Hi Aarti, great catch! \"Teratogenic\" (starts with \"tera\") relates to birth defects — think \"terrible for a baby.\" \"Tachycardic\" (starts with \"tachy\") is fast heart rate — like \"tachometer\" in a fast car. Want to try one more? Or take a deep breath and rest?"
    },
    {
      "turn": 6,
      "role": "user",
      "content": "One more, please… and then I’ll take a break. Promise."
    },
    {
      "turn": 6,
      "role": "maya",
      "content": "Hi Aarti, okay! Let’s try “mydriatic.” It’s for eye drops that make your pupils bigger. Think \"my\" (as in \"my eyes\") + \"dilate.\" Got it? You did so well with the others — take your break now, you’ve earned it."
    },
    {
      "turn": 7,
      "role": "user",
      "content": "Yeah, \"mydriatic\" makes sense now… thanks! My brain feels a tiny bit lighter. I’ll go sip some ginger tea and rest my eyes. Talk later, Miss Maya. 😊"
    },
    {
      "turn": 7,
      "role": "maya",
      "content": "Hi Aarti, ginger tea is a perfect pick — it warms up the mind and body. Rest well, and take your time. I'm here for more practice anytime you're ready. Talk soon!"
    },
    {
      "turn": 8,
      "role": "user",
      "content": "Thanks, Miss Maya! I’ll take your advice. These chats actually help me feel less stuck. Aapki baat sunke thodi roshni lagti hai. Goodnight! 🌙"
    },
    {
      "turn": 8,
      "role": "maya",
      "content": "Hi Aarti, \"Aapki baat sunke thodi roshni lagti hai\" — what a beautiful way to say that! You're doing great, just a tiny tweak: we say \"sunke\" without the \"ke\" at the end. Rest well, and I'll be here for your next chat. Goodnight!"
    }
  ],
